<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>What was the significance of the Knights of Labor in the 1880s?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It was the first major national labor organization to include both skilled and unskilled workers</option>
            <option letter="b">It represented only skilled craftsmen</option>
            <option letter="c">It focused exclusively on wage increases</option>
            <option letter="d">It operated only in major cities</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The Knights of Labor was revolutionary for including all workers regardless of skill level, race, or gender (except Chinese workers), reaching nearly 700,000 members at its peak in 1886.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>How did the Haymarket Affair of 1886 impact the labor movement?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It led to public backlash against unions and weakened the Knights of Labor</option>
            <option letter="b">It strengthened public support for unions</option>
            <option letter="c">It resulted in improved working conditions</option>
            <option letter="d">It had no effect on union membership</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The violence at Haymarket Square and subsequent trials created public fear of unions and anarchism, leading to declining membership in the Knights of Labor and setbacks for the labor movement.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>What was the primary goal of the American Federation of Labor when founded in 1886?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">To organize skilled workers by craft and focus on practical economic goals</option>
            <option letter="b">To promote socialist revolution</option>
            <option letter="c">To organize all workers regardless of skill</option>
            <option letter="d">To focus on political reform</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The AFL, under Samuel Gompers, focused on organizing skilled workers by craft and pursuing practical goals like higher wages and better working conditions rather than broad social reform.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>What impact did the Great Railroad Strike of 1877 have on American labor relations?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It demonstrated the power of organized labor and the willingness of government to use force against strikes</option>
            <option letter="b">It resulted in immediate improvements for workers</option>
            <option letter="c">It led to widespread public support for railroads</option>
            <option letter="d">It had minimal impact on labor organization</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The Great Railroad Strike of 1877 was the first major nationwide strike, showing both the potential power of organized labor and the government's readiness to use military force to suppress labor unrest.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
